<Layout
	lang="en"
	title="Sea destinations — Gandía 2026"
	description="Coastal destinations on the Spanish Mediterranean for your eclipse holiday — Gandía, Valencia, Benidorm, the calas of the Marina Alta and the Costa Blanca."
	otherLangHref="/es/mar/"
	otherLangLabel="Español"
>
	<p class="eyebrow">Sea destinations</p>
	<h1>By <span class="accent">the sea</span></h1>
	<p class="tagline">
		The Spanish Mediterranean coast — long beaches, warm shallow water,
		fishing-town dinners that run late.
	</p>

	<p>
		The most extraordinary part of this coast is the <strong>calas</strong> —
		small, clear-water coves tucked between pine-covered cliffs, just south of
		the main beaches. Their beauty is the unrepeatable kind, found in the
		narrow places where <strong>the mountains drop straight into the
		sea</strong>: a single bend in the road, a footpath through the pines,
		then a turquoise crescent caught between two ridges. Cala Granadella, near
		Xàbia, is the most famous of them; voted Spain's best beach more than
		once. Snorkel along the rocks, paddle a kayak out to the sea caves, hike
		the cliff path for the view from above, picnic in the shade of the pines,
		or eat at the chiringuito above the cove. We organise the gear, the
		boats, the picnic, the table.
	</p>

	<p>
		The calas are only half of this coast. The other half is the
		opposite of hidden: kilometre after kilometre of
		<strong>fine, pale-gold sand</strong> running flat and straight from
		Gandía south through Daimús, Piles and Oliva, and on toward Dénia.
		The water shelves so gently you can wade out fifty metres and still
		touch bottom; the sand is soft enough to cross barefoot at midday.
		In places the beach is backed by <strong>protected dunes</strong> —
		wooden walkways, marram grass, almost no buildings in sight. These
		are the beaches for long afternoons, long walks, long evenings.
	</p>

	<div class="gallery gallery-3">
